name: N,N'-diphenylurea
Reason: The compound N,N'-diphenylurea has several functional groups that influence its melting point. The base phenyl rings provide a significant structure. For example, benzene, the base unit of the phenyl ring, has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. Introducing the urea functional group (–NH–CO–NH–) increases the melting point considerably because of its ability to participate in hydrogen bonding and the strong dipole-dipole interactions it introduces. The two phenyl rings connected by the urea group also provide significant pi-pi stacking which stabilizes the solid phase. A standard primary amide raises the boiling point by approximately 80-100 degrees Celsius above an alkane with similar molar mass due to hydrogen bonding. Here we have a urea which is a bis-amide structure. Considering symmetry and enhanced hydrogen bonding, we may assume that the effect of the urea functional group would be approximately double that of a single amide group. Thus, if an amide has an effect of +90, urea could contribute around +180. Finally, additional van der Waals forces provided by the two additional phenyl rings combined should increase the melting point as well, this increment could be estimated to be less significant (+20 each) as the main effect comes from the possibility of hydrogen bonding of the urea group.
Prediction: The predicted melting point considering the base value for benzene of 5.5, adding the effect of the urea group (+180), and the two phenyl rings (+40 in total), gives us 5.5 + 180 + 40 = 225.5 degrees Celsius.
